WEBVTT

03:16.827 --> 03:23.733
We'd like for you to make some comments, if you 
would please, on what George McGinney did in

03:16.827 --> 03:23.733
ecology.

03:26.375 --> 03:39.727
George McGinney was, I believe, one of the first 
pure scientist marine ecologists in the world. I

03:41.388 --> 03:46.733
think that Peterson in Denmark was certainly an 
ecologist, but he was motivated by fishery

03:47.590 --> 03:58.540
concerns and did some very nice work. But George 
McGinnity, who is still alive, I heard just the

03:58.600 --> 04:17.277
other day, did

03:58.600 --> 04:17.277
some very nice work on the ecology of some of our 
estuarine conditions in California and on the

04:17.763 --> 04:23.589
West Coast in general. He tried to bring together 
all of the environmental factors, including the

04:26.132 --> 04:43.990
biological, that were controlling

04:26.132 --> 04:43.990
the ecosystems, although he did not call them 
ecosystems, in these estuarine areas. for the

04:45.117 --> 04:56.493
first time, and I think that he had a grasp of this 
that was admirable in his time. He doesn't fare

04:57.835 --> 05:11.395
well now because of the fact that things have 
progressed on into systems analysis and so on, and

04:57.835 --> 05:11.395
he had no respect for the attempts of biologists to 
become engineers. So he's not as well received now

05:17.734 --> 05:23.240
as he was in the past. But he was a pioneer, I would 
say, in his field. You know where he lives now? I am

05:31.629 --> 05:32.530
not certain. I surmise it is in Puget Sound region 
somewhere. I would say possibly. in the Friday

05:40.417 --> 05:42.539
Harbor region. His wife, Nettie McGinnity, they 
have published together. They've put out two or

05:48.967 --> 05:50.829
three books. So he is a real pioneer and would be, if 
he could be located, oh, Joel Hedgepath would know

05:52.190 --> 06:01.120
where he is. Just ask Joel, and you might want to 
give him a call or something. This is a quote,

